1170","1077":"1077","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1225":"1225","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1177":"1177","1155":"1155","about 1169":"about 1169","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","about 1175":"about 1175","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Wich Malbank, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Headington, Oxfordshire, England":"Headington, Oxfordshire, England","Heddington, Wiltshire, England":"Heddington, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Malbank","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Malbon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Malbon","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): nickname or habitational name from Norman French <i>Malbanc</i>, which may be from Old French <i>mal banc</i> ‘bad bench’, but if so the reason for the use of this expression as a surname is unknown. Possibly it derives from a lost placename, in which <i>banc</i> may mean ‘steep crag’. The second part of the name, <i>-banc</i>, survives in   Maybank  , but medieval forms in <i>-ban(e)</i>, <i>-bon(e)</i>, or <i>-bun</i> are also common and are sometimes later re-interpreted as <i>-born</i> and <i>-bourne</i>, leading to confusion with   Melbourne  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Malbank 3rd Baron of Wich Malbank was born in 1125, in Headington, Oxfordshire, England, his father, William Malbank II, was 45 and his mother, Petronilla Scudamore, was 48. He married Andilicia de Beauchamp before 1169, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 daughters. He died in 1177, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1125–1177":"1125–1177","1155–1185":"1155–1185","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1169–1225":"1169–1225","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1171–1260":"1171–1260","1175–1219":"1175–1219","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1077–Female":"1077–Surnud","1080":"1080","before 1169":"enne 1169","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1077":"1077","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1225":"1225","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1177":"1177","1155":"1155","about 1169":"umbes 1169","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Wich Malbank, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Headington, Oxfordshire, England":"Headington, Oxfordshire, England","Heddington, Wiltshire, England":"Heddington, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1125–1177":"1125–1177","1155–1185":"1155–1185","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","1169–1225":"1169–1225","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1171–1260":"1171–1260","1175–1219":"1175–1219","1208–Female":"1208–Kuollut","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1077–Female":"1077–Kuollut","1080":"1080","before 1169":"ennen vuotta 1169","about 1170":"noin 1170","1077":"1077","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1225":"1225","1125":"1125","1169":"1169","1177":"1177","1155":"1155","about 1169":"noin 1169","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","about 1175":"noin 1175","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Wich Malbank, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"Engla